                </div>

                <div class="speaker-notes">
                    Reflective models are essential for continuous improvement in digital leadership. Gibbs' cycle
                    provides a structured approach to learning from experiences, particularly valuable in fast-paced
                    digital environments. Schön's concepts of reflection-in-action and reflection-on-action are enhanced
                    by real-time data and feedback in digital environments. Digital tools facilitate reflection through
                    automated feedback systems, 360-degree reviews, and learning analytics that provide insights into
                    leadership effectiveness. Amazon's "Day 1" culture emphasizes continuous experimentation and
                    learning from failures through post-mortems that are shared company-wide. Google conducts detailed
                    project post-mortems to extract lessons and improve future initiatives. These models help digital
                    leaders adapt quickly to changing circumstances.
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- SLIDE 13: GIBBS' REFLECTIVE CYCLE IN LEADERSHIP -->
            <div class="slide" id="slide-13">
                <div class="header-icon"><i class="fas fa-redo"></i></div>
                <div class="content">
                    <h2>Gibbs' Reflective Cycle in Leadership</h2>
                    <div class="visualization">
                        <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1551288049-bebda4e38f71?ixlib=rb-4.0.3&auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80"
                            alt="Gibbs' Reflective Cycle Visualization" class="visual-img">
                    </div>
                    <ul>
                        <li><i class="fas fa-clipboard-list"></i> <strong>Description:</strong> What happened in the
                            digital project? (Airbnb's data-driven approach)</li>
                        <li><i class="fas fa-heart"></i> <strong>Feelings:</strong> How did the team respond to changes?
                            (Surveys, sentiment analysis)</li>
                        <li><i class="fas fa-clipboard-check"></i> <strong>Evaluation:</strong> What worked well/poorly?
                            (Metrics and KPIs)</li>
                        <li><i class="fas fa-search"></i> <strong>Analysis:</strong> Why did certain approaches succeed?
                            (Root cause analysis)</li>
                        <li><i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> <strong>Conclusion:</strong> What could have been done
                            differently? (Expert review)</li>
